// ----------------- INTERFACE -----------------
interface IAccount {
    void deposit(double amt);                // Deposit money into the account
    void withdraw(double amt) throws Exception; // Withdraw money; throws exception if invalid
    double getBalance();                      // Get current balance
    int getAccountId();                        // Get account ID
    String getName();                          // Get account holder's name
}
✅ Explanation:
Purpose: The interface defines common behaviors for any type of bank account.

Methods:

deposit(double amt) → Adds money to the account

withdraw(double amt) → Deducts money; throws exception if amount is invalid or insufficient

getBalance() → Returns current account balance

getAccountId() → Returns account ID

getName() → Returns account holder’s name

Implementation: Any class that represents a bank account (like SavingsAccount or CurrentAccount) must implement all methods of IAccount.

Example implementation in a class:

java
Copy code
class SavingsAccount implements IAccount {
    private int id;
    private String name;
    private double balance;

    public SavingsAccount(int id, String name, double balance) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
        this.balance = balance;
    }

    @Override
    public void deposit(double amt) {
        if (amt <= 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid deposit");
        balance += amt;
    }

    @Override
    public void withdraw(double amt) throws Exception {
        if (amt <= 0 || amt > balance) throw new Exception("Invalid withdraw");
        balance -= amt;
    }

    @Override
    public double getBalance() { return balance; }

    @Override
    public int getAccountId() { return id; }

    @Override
    public String getName() { return name; }
}
This demonstrates OOP abstraction and interface implementation clearly.
